fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
Let V be a vector space over \mathbb {F}, let v_{1},…,v_{m}\in  V be vectors. We define the Span of v_{1}, …, v_{m} to be
\mathrm {span}(v_{1},…,v_{m})=\{a_{1}v_{1}+…+a_{m}v_{m}\mid  a_{1},…,a_{m}\in \mathbb {F}\}
Moreover, the \mathrm {span}(v_{1},…,v_{m}) is a subspace of V.

Let V be a vector space over \mathbb {F}, we say v_{1},…,v_{m}\in  V are Linearly Independent if the only coefficients a_{1},…,a_{m}\in \mathbb {F} satisfying
a_{1}v_{1}+…+a_{m}v_{m}=\vec {0}
is a_{1}=…=a_{m}=0.

Consider I\mathrel {\trianglelefteq } R being a maximal ideal of R by Krull's theorem. Then we know R/I is field, let us call it
\mathbb {F} := R/I.
We also have a surjective ring morphism R\twoheadrightarrow \mathbb {F}. Let
\varphi \colon  R^{m}\to  R^{n}
be an isomorphism. Then we have the commutative diagram

  \usepackage {quiver, amsopn, amssymb, mathrsfs}
  \begin {tikzcd}
    R^{m}\ar [d, two heads]\ar [r, "\varphi "] & R^{n}\ar [d, two heads]\\
    \mathbb {F}^{m} & \mathbb {F}^{n}
  \end {tikzcd}


We can think of \varphi \colon  R^{m}\to  R^{n} using a matrix A as \varphi (x)=Ax.
